# Instructional Design Skill: Visual Design Principles 
for E-Learning

## Overview
Visual design in e-learning is the practice of using 
layout, typography, color, imagery, and visual hierarchy 
to support learning — not just to make courses look 
attractive. Good visual design reduces cognitive load, 
directs attention, establishes credibility, and makes 
content easier to process and retain. Poor visual design 
distracts, confuses, and undermines even the best 
instructional content. This skill helps Claude support 
instructional designers in applying core visual design 
principles to e-learning screens, templates, and assets 
with confidence and intentionality.

---

## Core Principle: Every Visual Decision Either 
Supports or Competes with Learning
Visual design is not decoration. Every color, font, 
image, and layout choice either helps the learner 
process and retain the content — or adds noise 
that works against it.

The question to ask of every visual decision is not 
*"Does this look good?"* but *"Does this help 
the learner?"*

---

## The Foundational Principles: CRAP

The four foundational principles of visual design — 
summarized by Robin Williams in *The Non-Designer's 
Design Book* — apply directly to e-learning screens:

### Contrast
Elements that are different should look 
clearly different. Contrast creates visual 
interest, establishes hierarchy, and 
directs attention.

- **Size contrast:** large headlines vs. 
  smaller body text
- **Color contrast:** dark text on light 
  background (or vice versa)
- **Weight contrast:** bold headings vs. 
  regular body copy
- **Style contrast:** icon vs. text, 
  image vs. white space

**Common mistake:** Low contrast between 
text and background — the most common 
and most easily prevented visual error.

### Repetition
Repeat visual elements throughout the course 
to create consistency and unity.

- Consistent fonts, colors, and button styles
- Consistent placement of navigation elements
- Consistent treatment of similar content types 
  (all scenario setups look the same, 
  all knowledge checks look the same)
- Consistent use of icons and imagery style

**Common mistake:** Inconsistent visual treatment 
of similar content — learners spend cognitive 
energy adapting to visual variation rather 
than focusing on content.

### Alignment
Every element on a screen should be 
visually connected to something else. 
Random placement creates visual noise.

- Align text to a consistent left, center, 
  or right edge
- Align images to text columns or grid lines
- Use invisible grid lines to organize 
  screen elements
- Avoid placing elements arbitrarily — 
  every position should be intentional

**Common mistake:** Centered everything — 
center alignment is appropriate for 
headlines and short text, but body text 
and mixed elements read better left-aligned.

### Proximity
Group related items together. 
Separate unrelated items clearly.

- Labels close to the elements they describe
- Related bullet points grouped together
- White space between unrelated sections
- Captions directly below (not beside) images

**Common mistake:** Equal spacing between 
all elements — this eliminates the visual 
grouping that tells learners what belongs together.

