## Typography

Typography choices significantly affect 
readability, tone, and cognitive load.

### Choosing Fonts

**Serif fonts** (Times New Roman, Georgia)
- Traditional, formal, authoritative
- Good for print; less ideal for screen 
  at small sizes

**Sans-serif fonts** (Arial, Helvetica, 
Open Sans, Lato)
- Clean, modern, highly readable on screen
- The standard choice for e-learning body text

**Display fonts** (decorative, script, slab)
- Use for headlines only, if at all
- Never use for body text
- Ensure they match the organizational tone

**The two-font rule:**
Use a maximum of two typefaces in a course — 
one for headings, one for body text. 
More than two creates visual noise.

### Font Sizing
Minimum sizes for screen readability:

| Element | Minimum Size |
|---|---|
| Body text | 16px / 12pt |
| Captions | 14px / 10pt |
| Headings | 24px / 18pt+ |
| Mobile body text | 18px / 14pt |

Never sacrifice readability for aesthetics.

### Line Length and Spacing
- **Optimal line length:** 50–75 characters 
  per line for body text
- Too long → eye loses its place
- Too short → choppy reading rhythm
- **Line height:** 1.4–1.6x the font size 
  for comfortable reading
- **Letter spacing:** default for body text; 
  slightly increased for all-caps headlines

### Avoid
- More than two typefaces
- All-caps body text (harder to read)
- Justified text in e-learning 
  (creates uneven spacing on screen)
- Font sizes below 14px for any learner-facing text
- Decorative fonts for anything other 
  than large display headlines

