## Layout and White Space

### The Grid
E-learning screens benefit from an 
invisible underlying grid that organizes 
all elements into a coherent structure.

- Divide the screen into columns 
  (typically 2, 3, or 4)
- Align all elements to grid lines
- Maintain consistent margins and gutters
- Never place elements at arbitrary positions

Most authoring tools offer guide lines 
or snap-to-grid features — use them.

### White Space
White space (also called negative space) 
is the empty area between and around elements. 
It is not wasted space — it is essential 
to visual clarity.

White space:
- Reduces cognitive load
- Groups and separates content visually
- Makes text more readable
- Creates a sense of quality and calm

**Common mistake:** Filling every pixel — 
crowded screens feel stressful and 
are harder to process.

### Screen Density
As a general rule, e-learning screens 
should feel lighter than they need to. 
If a screen looks full, remove something.

Guidelines:
- No more than 70–75 words of body text 
  per screen
- One main visual element per screen
- Generous margins — at least 10% of 
  screen width on each side
- Breathing room between all elements

