## Visual Design for Specific E-Learning Elements

### Title Screens and Module Openers
- Strong, clear headline
- Relevant, high-quality image
- Minimal text — this is an entry point, 
  not a content screen
- Tone-setting — visual mood should 
  match content gravity

### Content Screens
- Clear visual hierarchy — 
  what to read first is obvious
- Supporting image that adds meaning, 
  not just decoration
- Body text chunked — no walls of text
- Consistent placement of recurring elements

### Scenario Screens
- Character images that are expressive 
  and relatable
- Environment that establishes context
- Dialogue clearly attributed to speaker
- Decision options visually distinct 
  from content

### Knowledge Check Screens
- Consistent visual treatment across 
  all questions — learners should 
  recognize the format immediately
- Question stem visually separate 
  from answer options
markdown
- Answer options clearly delineated — 
  not crowded together
- Feedback clearly distinct from 
  question content

### Infographics and Data Visualization
- One key message per visualization
- Data labeled directly (not in a legend 
  that requires cross-referencing)
- Color used to group, not just decorate
- Simplest chart type that communicates 
  the data accurately
- Text alternative provided for 
  screen reader users

