## Visual Design and Cognitive Load

Visual design decisions directly affect 
cognitive load — the mental effort 
required to process a screen.

### Visual Choices That Reduce Load
- Clear hierarchy — learners know 
  where to look
- Consistent layout — learners aren't 
  reorienting with every screen
- Sufficient white space — 
  fewer competing elements
- Images that illustrate rather than decorate
- Typography that aids readability

### Visual Choices That Increase Load
- Too many colors, fonts, or styles
- Cluttered screens with no clear hierarchy
- Decorative animation that plays automatically
- Inconsistent placement of navigation elements
- Low contrast text requiring extra effort to read

